metadata.song: Terraria Calamity Mod - Guardian o The Former Seas
metadata.editComments:
The first of many boss battle themes in the Terraria Calamity Mod's soundtrack, "Guardian Of The Former Seas" is the theme for the fight against the Desert Scourge boss: in story, a giant, dried-up worm, the former apex predator of a now-desertified ocean, barely clinging on to life in a mindless hunt.

This intro has some really nice chords, featuring both the darkness of Phrygian's bIImaj7 and the bittersweetness of Dorian/Major's ii7 and Imaj7. Fitting for the scene of a budding adventurer and soon-to-be world-saving (anti)-hero hunting down an ancient, now-withered leviathan in a fight to the death.

metadata.song: Terraria Calamity Mod - Guardian o The Former Seas
metadata.editComments: I was going to write another essay on this section, but that bugged out the uploading system. So basically, chords are simpler, but guitar is cooler.

metadata.song: Terraria Calamity Mod - Guardian o The Former Seas
Terraria Calamity Mod - Guardian o The Former Seas
metadata.editComments: ...we end up arriving at the chorus. The energy and volume are at an all-time high, both parties are at their most serious, and the harmony's a double-time reprise of the intro. The lead's all in the hands of the guitar, and it's sticking pretty heavily to a tresillo rhythm. Whether that's supposed to represent the worm charging full-speed at the hooded freak trying to put it down, or your morally questionable hero(es) throwing whatever they have on hand at a foul beast with great bravado and rhythm, I don't know. Aside from that, there's nothing else about the chorus other than it's awesome.

metadata.song: Terraria Calamity Mod - Guardian o The Former Seas
metadata.editComments: The song, and (hopefully) the fight's drawing to an end, but it's going out with FURY. The lead's back to a steel pan, but it's playing a BLAZING solo over the chaos ensuing underneath. Meanwhile, the harmony's taken over by the guitars, and they're playing the same tresillo pattern from before, and the drums are just as angry. The harmony's the same as the chorus, but LOUDER, and overall the intensity is at its all-time high. Both you and the Scourge are on your last legs (or skins), and you won't stop until the other is dead. And as night draws, you're drawing closer and closer into eventual victory, and then... blam. Last blow. No matter what or how the final blow went, the Scourge passes in a gory explosion, and the victory is yours for the taking. Unless, of course, your sword's too dull. Or you're dumb. In that case, the song repeats.
